    "<|architect|>How would you structure a Python web application?<|assistant|Recommended structure for a Python web app:\n\nmyapp/\n  app.py              # Application factory and config\n  models/             # Database models\n    __init__.py\n    user.py\n    task.py\n  routes/             # API endpoints\n    __init__.py\n    auth.py\n    tasks.py\n  services/           # Business logic\n    __init__.py\n    auth_service.py\n    task_service.py\n  middleware/          # Request processing\n    auth.py\n    logging.py\n  utils/              # Helpers\n    validators.py\n    errors.py\n  tests/              # Test files\n    test_auth.py\n    test_tasks.py\n  config.py           # Settings\n  requirements.txt\n\nKey principles:\n- Routes handle HTTP, services handle logic, models handle data\n- Dependency injection over global state\n- Configuration via environment variables\n- Tests mirror the source structure\n\nThis separation of concerns makes the codebase maintainable and testable.<|end|>",

    "<|architect|>Explain the MVC design pattern<|assistant|MVC (Model-View-Controller) separates an application into three components:\n\nModel: Data and business logic. Manages how data is stored, validated, and processed. Has no knowledge of the UI. Example: database queries, data validation rules.\n\nView: Presentation layer. Displays data to the user and captures input. Contains no business logic. Example: HTML templates, React components.\n\nController: The coordinator. Receives user input, interacts with the model, and selects the appropriate view. Example: route handlers, API endpoints.\n\nData flow: User -> Controller -> Model -> Controller -> View -> User\n\nBenefits:\n- Separation of concerns: each part has a single responsibility\n- Testability: models and controllers can be tested independently of the UI\n- Parallel development: frontend and backend teams work simultaneously\n- Maintainability: changes to the view do not affect business logic\n\nModern variations: MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) for frameworks like Vue/Angular, and MVP (Model-View-Presenter) for Android development.<|end|>",

    "<|architect|>What is the repository pattern?<|assistant|The Repository Pattern abstracts data access behind a common interface:\n\nclass UserRepository(ABC):\n    @abstractmethod\n    def get_by_id(self, user_id): pass\n    @abstractmethod\n    def get_all(self): pass\n    @abstractmethod\n    def save(self, user): pass\n    @abstractmethod\n    def delete(self, user_id): pass\n\nclass SQLUserRepository(UserRepository):\n    def __init__(self, db):\n        self.db = db\n    def get_by_id(self, user_id):\n        return self.db.query(User).get(user_id)\n\nclass InMemoryUserRepository(UserRepository):\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.users = {}\n    def get_by_id(self, user_id):\n        return self.users.get(user_id)\n\nBenefits:\n- Swap databases without changing business logic\n- Easy testing with in-memory implementations\n- Centralized query logic (no SQL scattered across codebase)\n- Enforce data access rules in one place\n\nThe business layer only depends on the abstract interface, never on the concrete implementation.<|end|>",

    "<|architect|>How do you design a REST API?<|assistant|REST API design principles:\n\n1. Use nouns for resources, not verbs:\n   GET /users (not /getUsers)\n   POST /users (not /createUser)\n   DELETE /users/123 (not /deleteUser/123)\n\n2. Use HTTP methods correctly:\n   GET: read (never modify)\n   POST: create new resource\n   PUT: full update\n   PATCH: partial update\n   DELETE: remove\n\n3. Use proper status codes:\n   200: OK, 201: Created, 204: No Content\n   400: Bad Request, 401: Unauthorized, 403: Forbidden, 404: Not Found\n   500: Internal Server Error\n\n4. Versioning: /api/v1/users\n5. Pagination: GET /users?page=2&limit=20\n6. Filtering: GET /users?role=admin&active=true\n7. Consistent error format: {\"error\": {\"code\": \"NOT_FOUND\", \"message\": \"User 123 not found\"}}\n\nKeep endpoints predictable. A good API is self-documenting through consistent patterns.<|end|>",

    "<|architect|>What are microservices vs monolith?<|assistant|Monolith: One codebase, one deployment, one database. Simple to develop and deploy initially. Gets harder as the team and codebase grow.\n\nMicroservices: Many small independent services, each with its own database and deployment. Services communicate via APIs or message queues.\n\nWhen to use monolith:\n- Small team (1-5 developers)\n- Early-stage startup validating an idea\n- Simple domain with clear boundaries\n- Need to ship fast\n\nWhen to use microservices:\n- Large team (10+ developers)\n- Need independent scaling of components\n- Different parts have different reliability requirements\n- Multiple deployment cycles needed\n\nThe trap: most teams start with microservices too early and pay the complexity cost (distributed debugging, network latency, data consistency) before they need to. Start monolithic, extract services when specific scaling problems emerge.<|end|>",
